   =20
      NFT Stuff
   =20
 =20
This is not technically a non-fungible token, but it does reinforce the ver=
y NFT-related idea that the most lucrative thing you can do to a work of ar=
t is to destroy it:A painting that British street artist Banksy purposely s=
hredded during a previous auction sold Thursday to an anonymous Asian colle=
ctor for $25.4 million at Sotheby=E2=80=99s in London, setting a new record=
 for the artist at auction. ...Now, the anonymous buyer of that $1.4 millio=
n work has had the last laugh=E2=80=94by reselling the ribboned work on Thu=
rsday for 18 times as much. Sotheby=E2=80=99s only expected it to sell for =
as much as $8 million, but at least nine bidders in the sale pushed its pri=
ce even higher, with the director of Sotheby=E2=80=99s private sales in Asi=
a, Nick Wood, fielding the winning telephone bid. =E2=80=9CI can=E2=80=99t =
tell you how nervous I am to drop the gavel on this one,=E2=80=9D said auct=
ioneer Oliver Barker in the moment, glancing at the work hanging behind him=
. Nothing followed but applause.If I were a painter, and I painted a painti=
ng and showed it to my dealer and she was like =E2=80=9Creally nice work Ma=
tt, good effort, but let me make a teeny suggestion, why don=E2=80=99t you =
SHRED IT INTO TINY BITS, those shreds will be worth more than this painting=
,=E2=80=9D I would be =E2=80=A6=C2=A0really offended? Like there I was putt=
ing all that work into the painting? But the incentives are what they are.I=
n =E2=80=9CAnimal Crackers,=E2=80=9D Chico Marx quotes Groucho a rate of $1=
0 per hour for playing music. =E2=80=9CWhat do you get for not playing,=E2=
=80=9D asks Groucho, and Chico says=C2=A0$12 an hour.Chico: Now, for rehear=
sing we make special rate. That=E2=80=99s=C2=A0fifteen dollars an hour.Grou=
cho: That=E2=80=99s for rehearsing?Chico: That's for rehearsing.Groucho: An=
d what do you get for not rehearsing?Chico: You couldn=E2=80=99t afford it.=
Sure Banksy can make=C2=A0money by selling his paintings, but he can make e=
ven more by shredding them. How much=C2=A0could he get for not painting the=
m at all?
