10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Bitcoin ETF</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you buy shares of an S&amp;P 500 in=
dex exchange-traded fund, what does the fund do with your money? There is a=
 technical answer about in-kind creation and authorized participants that I=
 am going to ignore here[1] to just say: The fund takes your money and uses=
 it to buy shares of the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/25354789.265956/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZm94YnVzaW5lc3MuY29tL21hcmtldHMvaG93=
LW1hbnktc3RvY2tzLWFyZS1pbi10aGUtc3AtNTAwLWEtbG9vay1hdC1zdGFuZGFyZC1hbmQtcG9=
vcnMtZ3Jvd3Ro/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB947b723b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">500ish</a> stocks =
in the S&amp;P 500. If you slice open the S&amp;P 500 ETF, you will find a =
bunch of stocks. It owns stocks. When you own shares of the S&amp;P 500 ETF=
, you own a portion of the big pot of stocks that it owns.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">If you buy shares of a Bitcoin ETF, what does the fund do w=
ith your money? Again I will ignore technical=C2=A0creation mechanics. Also=
 of course this is a trick question, you cannot (in the U.S.) buy shares of=
 a Bitcoin ETF, Bitcoin ETFs do not exist. But soon they will, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25354789.265956/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMTUvYml0Y29pbi1mdXR1cmVzL=
WV0Zi1zYWlkLW5vdC10by1mYWNlLXNlYy1vcHBvc2l0aW9uLWF0LWRlYWRsaW5l/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cBcf37ec07" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Katie Greifeld, Vildan=
a Hajric and Benjamin Bain report</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission is poised to allow the first=
 U.S. Bitcoin futures exchange-traded fund to begin trading in a watershed =
moment for the cryptocurrency industry, according to people familiar with t=
he matter.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The regulator isn=E2=80=99t like=
ly to block the products from starting to trade next week, said the people,=
 who asked not to be named while discussing the decision. Unlike Bitcoin ET=
F applications that the regulator has previously rejected, the proposals by=
 ProShares and Invesco Ltd. are based on futures contracts and were filed u=
nder mutual fund rules that SEC Chairman Gary Gensler has said provide =E2=
=80=9Csignificant investor protections.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So what will the Bitcoin ETF do with your money? T=
he answer is[2]:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40=
px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It will put about=
 30% of the money into a collateral account at a U.S. registered commodity =
futures exchange, to collateralize positions in cash-settled Bitcoin future=
s. The futures exchange will presumably hold=C2=A0the collateral in bank ac=
counts or Treasury bills or whatever.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5p=
x;">It will put=C2=A0about 70% of the money into money-market securities, T=
reasury bills or high-grade commercial paper or whatever.</li></ol><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Basically if you slice open the Bitcoin ETF you will f=
ind a bunch of (U.S. dollar)=C2=A0cash equivalents. Plus a cash-settled bet=
 with a futures exchange that the price of Bitcoin will go up. If Bitcoin g=
oes up, the ETF will get more cash to plop into money-market securities. If=
 Bitcoin goes down, the ETF will have to sell some of those securities to h=
and over some cash. If Bitcoin doubles, the ETF=E2=80=99s cash will more or=
 less double; if Bitcoin goes to zero, the ETF=E2=80=99s cash will more or =
less disappear.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The ETF holds a synthetic B=
itcoin: cash, plus a derivative to make that cash go up and down with the p=
rice of Bitcoin. Somebody is manufacturing that synthetic Bitcoin for the E=
TF. Probably that someone is an arbitrage trader on the futures exchange, a=
nd probably the main ingredient it is=C2=A0using to manufacture the synthet=
ic Bitcoin is a real Bitcoin.[3] The trade is roughly:</p><ol style=3D"list=
-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">The arbitrageur gets together $60,000 and buys one Bit=
coin on a Bitcoin exchange, keeping it in custody on the exchange or in the=
 arbitrageur=E2=80=99s own Bitcoin wallet.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">The arbitrageur sells one cash-settled Bitcoin future on a registe=
red futures exchange, posting $20,000 of collateral with the exchange to en=
sure that it will pay up on the bet.[4]</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: =
5px;">If the price of Bitcoin goes up, the arbitrageur has to put more cash=
 into the futures exchange to margin its position. The value of the Bitcoin=
 it holds goes up, but that doesn=E2=80=99t necessarily generate any cash; =
it=E2=80=99s not going to sell the Bitcoin.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">If the price of Bitcoin goes down, the arbitrageur gets some cash=
 out of the futures exchange. The value of the Bitcoin it holds goes down, =
but that doesn=E2=80=99t necessarily cost it any cash; it=E2=80=99s not goi=
ng to sell the Bitcoin.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you put $6=
0,000 into a Bitcoin ETF, it will post about $20,000 at the futures exchang=
e to collateralize one synthetic Bitcoin, and will keep the other $40,000 i=
n cash earning a bit of interest. Meanwhile the person selling it the synth=
etic Bitcoin has to put up about $80,000 to (1) buy the actual Bitcoin and =
(2) post margin at the futures exchange itself. That $80,000 isn=E2=80=99t =
free; you have to pay the arbitrageur for the use of its balance sheet.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, the person selling the synthetic Bitcoin=
 has to keep custody of the real Bitcoin it uses to manufacture the synthet=
ic Bitcoin. This is a problem that has <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/25354789.265956/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMTIvZG9uLXQtZm9yZ2V0LXlvdXItYml0Y29pbnM/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cBb7b21c35" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> become easier over time</a>, but it =
is still not entirely trivial; there is a lot more high-stakes remembering =
of passwords in the Bitcoin world than there is in the traditional financia=
l system. This also costs money.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So the peo=
ple manufacturing the synthetic Bitcoins for the ETF will=C2=A0<em>charge=
=C2=A0</em>for that service: They have to put up $80,000 of cash and then d=
o a lot of hard password-remembering to keep their Bitcoin, while the ETF o=
nly has to put up $20,000 of cash and take the relatively pleasant credit r=
isk of a registered U.S. commodity futures exchange. So if you buy a synthe=
tic Bitcoin =E2=80=94=C2=A0as the Bitcoin ETFs plan to =E2=80=94=C2=A0you h=
ave to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25354789.26=
5956/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9iaXRjb2luLWZhbnMtZmxvY2stdG8tdG=
hlLWZ1dHVyZXMtbWFya2V0LTExNjM0MjAzODAxP21vZD1pdHBfd3NqJnJ1PXlhaG9v/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB91dd7741" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">pay more for it than you would for a reg=
ular old Bitcoin</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In recent=
 days, the annualized premium on CME bitcoin futures prices over bitcoin=E2=
=80=99s spot value was 15%, compared with about 7.7% on average over the fi=
rst nine months of the year. Traders can make those returns by buying spot =
bitcoin and shorting the futures contract because the two prices will conve=
rge in the future, said Noelle Acheson, head of market insights at crypto l=
ender Genesis Global Trading Inc. She chalks the gap in the premium up to i=
nstitutions rushing to buy bitcoin futures in expectation of the ETFs=E2=80=
=99 approval. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But futures-based E=
TFs are vulnerable to divergences in the prices of the futures and the unde=
rlying assets they track=E2=80=94in this case bitcoin, which is notoriously=
 volatile.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">ETFs may also lag the performanc=
e of bitcoin if it keeps rising. Longer-dated bitcoin futures have tended t=
o trade above short-term contracts, a market dynamic known as contango. Thi=
s can lead to lower returns for funds as they pay to roll over monthly cont=
racts.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CA lot of people really don=
=E2=80=99t understand how futures work,=E2=80=9D said Kathleen Moriarty, an=
 ETF lawyer, of individual investors.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">The basic way that futures work is that you are paying someone else=
 to store your Bitcoins for you, which is expensive.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Why not just store the Bitcoins yourself? Really there are =
two questions there:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left=
: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Why doesn=E2=
=80=99t=C2=A0the ETF just store the Bitcoins itself? You give the ETF $60,0=
00 and, instead of spending that on money-market securities and futures mar=
gin, it just goes out and buys a Bitcoin.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">Why not just store the Bitcoins=C2=A0<em>yourself</em>? Don=E2=80=
=99t give the ETF anything; just pay $60,000 to someone with a Bitcoin and =
get the Bitcoin.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The answer to the fi=
rst question is essentially that the SEC is probably about to approve <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25354789.265956/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3NwZWVjaC9nZW5zbGVyLWZhbW5hYy0yMDIxLTA5LTI5/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB103c5634" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">futures-based Bitcoin ETFs</a>, but s=
eems to be considerably more skeptical about =E2=80=9Cphysical=E2=80=9D Bit=
coin ETFs, ETFs that would actually hold Bitcoins. This is, I suspect, most=
ly a matter of regulatory legibility: Bitcoin futures trade on registered U=
.S. futures exchanges,[5] and if weird stuff happens on those exchanges U.S=
. regulators have lots of power to investigate and intervene; Bitcoins them=
selves trade in lots of different places, many of them not subject to much =
U.S. regulatory oversight. Also physical custody of Bitcoins does seem to b=
e <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25354789.265956/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMC0zNDA/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB2fb2ef06" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">an issue that the SEC worries about</a>, an=
d if an SEC-approved physical Bitcoin ETF forgot its passwords and lost all=
 of its customers=E2=80=99 Bitcoins that would be really, really, really, r=
eally =E2=80=A6=C2=A0let=E2=80=99s not kid ourselves, it would be hilarious=
, but it would be really upsetting for the SEC. Whereas an ETF that just ho=
lds a pot of money-market instruments and some regulated exchange-traded fu=
tures is, you know, fairly normal.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The answ=
er to the second question is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0well, look, sure, go buy Bitcoi=
ns. Particularly if you think that Bitcoin is the future of the financial s=
ystem, etc., it seems a little silly to give your money to an ETF to put in=
to money-market instruments and bet on the price of Bitcoin. Just go to the=
 blockchain and buy a Bitcoin. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/25354789.265956/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydG=
ljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMTMvYml0Y29pbi1ldGYtYXBwcm92YWwtbWF5LWRpc2FwcG9pbnQtYnVsb=
HMtYmV0dGluZy1vbi1mcmVzaC1oaWdocw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5eb63933" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
"> Greifeld reports</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Given =
the ease of access to cryptocurrency markets relative to previous years, it=
=E2=80=99s unclear that a Bitcoin ETF launch would spark a flood of demand,=
 according to Juthica Chou, head of over-the-counter options trading at Kra=
ken Digital Asset Exchange. Individuals can already buy and sell digital as=
sets on crypto exchanges worldwide and through more retail-oriented platfor=
ms such as PayPal and Square. Meanwhile, institutional investors have been =
able to gain crypto exposure through vehicles such as the Grayscale Bitcoin=
 Trust -- though plagued by persistent discounts -- for years.=C2=A0</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9COnboarding for individual investors, for=
 retail, for institutions is already a lot better and safer and more approa=
chable than let=E2=80=99s say crypto was back in 2017,=E2=80=9D Chou said o=
n Bloomberg=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CQuickTake Stock=E2=80=9D streaming program.<=
/p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Back in 2017, when regulated B=
itcoin futures were launching in the U.S.,=C2=A0owning physical Bitcoins wa=
s so unpleasant that I wrote a column with the headline <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25354789.265956/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTctMTItMTkvYml0Y29pbi1mdXR1cmVzLWFy=
ZS1hLWdyZWF0LXdheS10by1ub3Qtb3duLWJpdGNvaW4/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdeba8d=
e1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> =E2=80=9CBitcoin Futures Are a Great Way to Not Own Bitcoin</=
a>.=E2=80=9D Since then it has gotten much better. You can just go <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25354789.265956/aHR0cHM6L=
y9yb2Jpbmhvb2QuY29tL3VzL2VuL2Fib3V0L2NyeXB0by8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6a4=
02aca" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">buy actual Bitcoins</a> on the Robinhood app; why would Robi=
nhood users want a Bitcoin ETF? Institutions have to think more about custo=
dy issues, but institutions that want to own Bitcoin=C2=A0<em>have=C2=A0</e=
m>spent the last four years thinking about custody issues and now there are=
, you know, institutional custodians and best practices for remembering pas=
swords and so forth.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still my <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25354789.265956/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMDcvbWF0dC1sZXZpbmUtcy=
1tb25leS1zdHVmZi1sb29raW5nLWZvci10ZXRoZXItcy1tb25leQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB219ca6cd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> basic thinking</a> on crypto <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25354789.265956/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZX=
JnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDEtMDkvYmxvY2tjaGFpbi1zdG9jay1vZmZlc=
mluZ3MtYW5kLXN0YWJsZWNvaW5zLXdpbGwtZW5oYW5jZS1jcnlwdG8/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cB338d60f2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">is often</a> that there is a crypto financial system=
 and a traditional financial system, and they run on different rails, and t=
here are costs and frictions in switching between them. If you are a crypto=
 trader, it is irritating enough to transact in U.S. dollars that you=E2=80=
=99ll go use a weird stablecoin in order to send dollars using crypto rails=
. If you are a traditional-finance=C2=A0hedge fund, it might be irritating =
enough to transact in Bitcoins that you=E2=80=99ll go use a weird ETF in or=
der to buy Bitcoins using traditional rails. Someone (the ETF provider, the=
 futures arbitrageur, the stablecoin entrepreneur) is making money from tho=
se products; you are paying them that money for the service of doing the ra=
il-switching so you don=E2=80=99t have to.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
I suppose that could last forever. In some sense gold is not fully integrat=
ed into the global financial system, insofar as gold is heavy and you can=
=E2=80=99t transfer it as easily as you can a stock certificate, but there =
are various tools (gold futures, ETFs, etc.) designed to shoehorn gold into=
 the regular system so that a hedge fund that wants gold exposure can get i=
t from its broker in a fairly straightforward, electronic, sitting-at-your-=
desk-looking-at-screens sort of=C2=A0way. Bitcoin =E2=80=94=C2=A0crypto gen=
erally =E2=80=94=C2=A0could be a similar=C2=A0niche product, hard to get yo=
ur hands on, but connected to the traditional financial system by functiona=
l but somewhat kludgy interfaces.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But doesn=
=E2=80=99t that seem unlikely? Certainly crypto enthusiasts have grand plan=
s for taking over the traditional financial system, for making stocks and b=
onds and interest-rate derivatives and mortgages trade on the blockchain. F=
or that matter, the traditional financial system also tends to express a lo=
t of enthusiasm for blockchains. It just seems implausible to me that in 10=
 years crypto will still be big and we=E2=80=99ll still be talking about ho=
w hard it is to switch between your brokerage account and the blockchain, o=
r that there will be big lucrative businesses of =E2=80=9Cputting dollars o=
n the blockchain=E2=80=9D (stablecoins) or =E2=80=9Cputting Bitcoins into y=
our brokerage account=E2=80=9D (Bitcoin futures ETFs). Eventually crypto wi=
ll take over traditional finance or traditional finance will take over cryp=
to or everyone will just be comfortable transacting in both, and an ETF of =
synthetic Bitcoins will look sort of quaint.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-=
