om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Buying your way into the index?</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is what looks like a careful, tho=
ughtful empirical academic paper, =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/25354789.265956/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmJlci5vcmcvcGFwZX=
JzL3cyOTM2NQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB37d1df67" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Is Stock Index Memb=
ership for Sale?</a>=E2=80=9D by Xin Kun Li and Shang-Jin Wei,=C2=A0that re=
aches an intuitive and amusing conclusion that I simply do not believe:</p>=
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While major stock market indices a=
re followed by large monetary investments, we document that membership deci=
sions for the S&amp;P 500 index have a nontrivial amount of discretion. We =
show that firms=E2=80=99 purchases of S&amp;P ratings appear to improve the=
ir chance of entering the index (but purchases of Moody=E2=80=99s ratings d=
o not). Furthermore, firms tend to purchase more S&amp;P ratings when there=
 are openings in the index membership. Such a pattern is also confirmed by =
an event study that explores a rule change on index membership in 2002. Fin=
ally, discretionary additions exhibit subsequent deterioration in financial=
 performance relative to rule-based additions.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">The S&amp;P 500 is roughly speaking an index of the 500 bi=
ggest public companies, but it is not=C2=A0<em>exactly=C2=A0</em>that, and =
S&amp;P has a lot of discretion in choosing which companies to add to the i=
ndex. Being added to the index is good for a company=E2=80=99s stock price =
(and thus for its cost of financing). S&amp;P=C2=A0is a company that (1) ru=
ns this index but also (2) issues credit ratings on bonds, which the issuer=
s of those bonds pay it for. The contention here is that companies with a s=
hot at getting added to the index buy a lot of credit ratings from S&amp;P =
in order to make S&amp;P like them and add them to its index.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Don=E2=80=99t get me wrong, that is a very funny resul=
t and I am <em>generally</em> happy to believe that financial-services comp=
anies sometimes choose their own financial interests over the pursuit of ab=
stract truth. Also the paper has lots of very suggestive evidence of causal=
ity:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We sharpen our identificat=
ion with two additional exercises. First, we examine rating purchase behavi=
our during times when there is an opening in the index membership for reaso=
ns exogenous to these firms. In particular, mergers and acquisitions (M&amp=
;As) between existing S&amp;P 500 constituent firms create such an opening =
and are likely to be outside the control of the firms outside of the index.=
 ...=C2=A0We show that in the quarter with such a merger announcement, rela=
tively large firms outside the index tend to increase their purchases of S&=
amp;P ratings (but not of Moody=E2=80=99s ratings). =E2=80=A6</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another informative exercise is to use the S&amp;P 500=
 index rule change in 2002. The rule change excluded foreign firms from the=
 S&amp;P 500 index, resulting in seven foreign firms being ousted from the =
index. We use this 2002 event as an adverse shock to foreign firms=E2=80=99=
 incentive to compete for S&amp;P 500 membership. We use a difference-in-di=
fference (DID) setting and find that there is a reduction in S&amp;P rating=
 purchases by foreign firms in the quarters after the event. In addition, t=
he effect is more pronounced for large foreign firms and foreign firms from=
 the same countries as the removed members. When we repeat the exercise in =
firms=E2=80=99 purchases of Moody=E2=80=99s rating, we see no comparable be=
haviour. This reinforces the argument that firms purchase S&amp;P ratings p=
artly to curry favour in order to obtain membership in the index.</p></bloc=
kquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I just =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t k=
now, man, this seems like a very niche activity? Relatively few companies g=
et added to the index each year, so the sample of =E2=80=9Ccompanies that m=
ight get added to the S&amp;P if they just spend a bit more on S&amp;P rati=
ngs=E2=80=9D is small. Also it generally happens roughly once per company: =
You are not in the index, and then one quarter you get added, and then you =
are in the index for a while; you are not getting added and subtracted ever=
y year. There are no repeat players who say =E2=80=9Cah, yes, <em>I </em>kn=
ow how to win the game of getting added to the index.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Also yo=
u don=E2=80=99t generally just go to S&amp;P and say =E2=80=9Cgive me 10 ra=
tings please, here=E2=80=99s a big check=E2=80=9D; you =E2=80=9Cpurchase mo=
re S&amp;P ratings=E2=80=9D to the extent that you are=C2=A0<em>issuing mor=
e bonds</em>, which may or may not correlate with being added to the index =
but which is surely based more on your financing strategy than on the index=
. So the idea that companies are regularly sitting down and saying =E2=80=
=9Cwe are big enough to be in the S&amp;P 500 now, so let=E2=80=99s go buy =
a bunch of ratings so that S&amp;P looks favorably on us and adds us to the=
 index=E2=80=9D just strikes me as psychologically implausible. Who is the =
person at the company who even thinks to do that?=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Meanwhile at S&amp;P, I don=E2=80=99t know enough about the in=
ner workings of the S&amp;P 500 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/25354789.265956/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc3BnbG9iYWwuY29tL3NwZGppL2VuL=
2dvdmVybmFuY2Uv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9b0040b2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">membership selec=
tion committee</a> to be really confident about this, but it also seems psy=
chologically implausible to me that those people are sitting down saying li=
ke =E2=80=9Chere are 10 companies that qualify for the index, we can only p=
ick two, let=E2=80=99s pick the two who pay us the most.=E2=80=9D The S&amp=
;P 500 index is run by a joint venture called <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/25354789.265956/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3J=
nL3dpa2kvUyUyNlBfRG93X0pvbmVzX0luZGljZXM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB86fc46f6"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">S&amp;P Dow Jones=C2=A0Indices LLC</a>, which is majority-owned by=
 S&amp;P Global Inc. (the credit rating firm) but not identical with it. Do=
 the index people at this joint venture=C2=A0have access to S&amp;P=E2=80=
=99s ratings revenue information? I have no idea but it just seems weird to=
 me to imagine that they=E2=80=99d think this way. Again I absolutely do no=
t reject this sort of conflict of interest as a general matter! Just, here,=
 it seems real weird. Also <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/25354789.265956/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvYmY2NmQ2MDYtYj=
JhMi00Zjc5LWE5M2UtOTA4ZTdiYjk0MjVh/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf1dd5170" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
